The inequality becomes \(|u - 1| + |v - 1| \le 1\). - This inequality is symmetric in all four quadrants, so we can focus on the first quadrant and multiply the area by 4. 2. **First Quadrant Analysis**: - In the first quadrant (\(x \ge 0\) and \(y \ge 0\)), the inequality simplifies to \(|x - 1| + |y - 1| \le 1\). - We break this into cases based on the values of \(x\) and \(y\): - **Case 1**: \(x \ge 1\) and \(y \ge 1\): The inequality becomes \((x - 1) + (y - 1) \le 1\), forming a triangle with vertices \((1, 1)\), \((1, 2)\), and \((2, 1)\). - **Case 2**: \(x \ge 1\) and \(y < 1\): The inequality becomes \((x - 1) + (1 - y) \le 1\), forming a triangle with vertices \((1, 0)\), \((1, 1)\), and \((2, 1)\). - **Case 3**: \(x < 1\) and \(y \ge 1\): The inequality becomes \((1 - x) + (y - 1) \le 1\), forming a triangle with vertices \((0, 1)\), \((1, 1)\), and \((1, 2)\). - **Case 4**: \(x < 1\) and \(y < 1\): The inequality becomes \((1 - x) + (1 - y) \le 1\), forming a triangle with vertices \((1, 0)\), \((0, 1)\), and \((1, 1)\). 3. **Area Calculation**: - Each case in the first quadrant forms a triangle with area \(0.5\). - Summing the areas of these four triangles in the first quadrant gives \(0.5 + 0.5 + 0.5 + 0.5 = 2\). - Multiplying by 4 to account for all quadrants, the total area is \(4 \times 2 = 8\).
